	<h2 id="overview" class="vf-u-margin--0 vf-u-padding__top--400 vf-u-padding__bottom--600 vf-search-client-side--no-index">Overview</h2>
	<p>
		Graceful Degradation is a design approach that ensures systems continue to function even when parts fail or are not supported by the user’s environment.
	</p>
	<p>
		Instead of breaking completely, applications reduce non-essential features while preserving core functionality such as content access and navigation. This ensures usability across slow networks, older browsers, low-powered devices, or partial system failures.
	</p>
	<p>
		Originating from fault-tolerant system design, Graceful Degradation is widely used in web and distributed systems to maintain reliability and user trust. In web development, it typically means building for modern environments first, while still supporting older or constrained ones with a reduced but functional experience.
	</p>
	<h3>Key Idea In LRO Context</h3>
	<figure class="vf-figure vf-figure--align vf-figure--align-centered">
		<img src="{{ '/images/content_images/LRO diagram 2.3.a.avif' | url }}" alt="Aaron Walter's hierarchy of user needs" loading="lazy">
		<figcaption class="vf-figure__caption"></figcaption>
	</figure>
	<p>Within the Low Resource Optimisation (LRO) framework, Graceful Degradation ensures applications remain usable in constrained environments such as:</p>
	<ul class="vf-list vf-list--unordered">
		<li class="vf-list__item">Slow or unstable networks</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Low-end devices</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Older browsers</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Disabled or failing JavaScript/assets</li>
	</ul>
	<p>Core functionality is always preserved, even if advanced features fail.
Examples include:</p>
	<ul class="vf-list vf-list--unordered">
		<li class="vf-list__item">Text loads when images fail</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Cached data appears when APIs fail</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Basic forms work without JavaScript</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Simple layouts replace advanced CSS</li>
	</ul>

	<h2 id="why-lro" class="vf-u-margin--0 vf-u-padding__top--400 vf-u-padding__bottom--600">Why this matters for LRO</h2>
	<p>
		Graceful Degradation improves access for users in real-world constrained conditions.
	</p>
	<p>Constraints include:</p>
	<ul class="vf-list vf-list--unordered">
		<li class="vf-list__item"><strong>Slow networks</strong> → API timeouts or failed asset loads</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item"><strong>Low-end devices</strong> → limited CPU/memory</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item"><strong>Outdated browsers</strong> → limited support for modern CSS or JavaScript APIs</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item"><strong>Restricted environments</strong> → limited hardware capabilities and disabled JS or cookies</li>
	</ul>
	<p>
		Impact if ignored:
	</p>
	<ul class="vf-list vf-list--unordered">
		<li class="vf-list__item">Blank screens during load failures</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Broken workflows due to script errors</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Missing or inaccessible content due to unsupported technologies</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Complete application failure from minor issues</li>
	</ul>
	<p>Graceful Degradation prevents this by ensuring the system fails <strong>in pieces rather than all at once.</strong></p>

	<h2 id="common-problems" class="vf-u-margin--0 vf-u-padding__top--400 vf-u-padding__bottom--600">Common problems</h2>
	<h3>Typical issues seen</h3>
	<p>Modern web systems are complex and depend on many interconnected components.</p>
	<p>Common issues that trigger degraded states include:</p>
	<ul class="vf-list vf-list--unordered">
		<li class="vf-list__item"><strong>API Timeouts:</strong> Core information must always be accessible</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item"><strong>Network Failures:</strong> Enhancements should build on a reliable base</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item"><strong>Browser Compatibility Issues:</strong> Unsupported CSS features or JavaScript APIs</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item"><strong>Heavy Resource Requirements:</strong> Large frameworks overwhelming low-end devices</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item"><strong>Third-Party Dependency Failures:</strong> Analytics services or payment gateways becoming unavailable</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item"><strong>Server Overload:</strong> High traffic exceeding system capacity</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>Why these problems matter</h3>
	<p>When applications lack graceful fallback mechanisms, the failure of a single component can prevent the entire system from functioning.</p>
	<p>Examples include:</p>
	<ul class="vf-list vf-list--unordered">
		<li class="vf-list__item">An entire dashboard failing because one widget crashes</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">A page refusing to load because one script fails</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">A checkout system breaking due to a third-party payment service outage</li>
	</ul>
	<p>Graceful Degradation prevents these scenarios by allowing systems to maintain a reduced but functional experience.</p>

	<h3>Design Principles Involved</h3>
	<p>Several resilience and accessibility principles underpin Graceful Degradation.</p>
	<ul class="vf-list vf-list--unordered">
		<li class="vf-list__item"><strong>Fault Tolerance:</strong> Systems should continue operating even when components fail</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item"><strong>Resilience Engineering:</strong> Systems should absorb disruptions without catastrophic failure</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item"><strong>User-Centric Design:</strong> Users should still be able to complete essential tasks during failures</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item"><strong>Redundancy:</strong> Multiple alternatives should exist for critical functionality</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item"><strong>Fallback Design:</strong> Alternative methods should replace failing components</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item"><strong>Loose Coupling:</strong> Dependencies should not cause cascading failures</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item"><strong>Graceful Failure: </strong> Systems should degrade smoothly rather than abruptly stopping</li>
	</ul>

	<h2 id="implementation" class="vf-u-margin--0 vf-u-padding__top--400 vf-u-padding__bottom--600">Implementation guidance</h2>
	<h3>Practical Steps</h3>
	<ul class="vf-list vf-list--ordered">
		<li class="vf-list__item">
			<p>Identify Mission-Critical Functions</p>
			<p>Determine which features must always remain available.</p>
			<p>These typically include:</p>
			<ul class="vf-list vf-list--unordered">
				<li class="vf-list__item">Key content exists directly in the HTML</li>
				<li class="vf-list__item">Navigation links and forms work without JavaScript</li>
				<li class="vf-list__item">Semantic, accessible elements are used</li>
			</ul>
			<p>Everything else can degrade if necessary.</p>
		</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">
			<p>Build Redundancy</p>
			<p>Critical components should have fallback alternatives.</p>
			<p>Examples include:</p>
			<ul class="vf-list vf-list--unordered">
				<li class="vf-list__item">Multiple payment gateways</li>
				<li class="vf-list__item">Cached API responses</li>
				<li class="vf-list__item">Static HTML content replacing dynamic rendering</li>
			</ul>
			</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">
			<p>Support Older Browsers</p>
			<p>Applications should provide compatibility with older technologies.</p>
			<p>Techniques include:</p>
			<ul class="vf-list vf-list--unordered">
				<li class="vf-list__item">Using HTML5 alternatives instead of deprecated plugins</li>
				<li class="vf-list__item">Avoiding reliance on proprietary browser features</li>
				<li class="vf-list__item">Providing fallback styles</li>
			</ul>
			</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">
			<p>Use Load Balancing And Caching</p>
			<p>Distributing traffic across servers prevents any single system from becoming overloaded. Caching provides fallback data when live services fail.</p>
			</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">
			<p>Test Under Failure Conditions</p>
			<p>Systems should be tested under various scenarios, such as:</p>
			<ul class="vf-list vf-list--unordered">
				<li class="vf-list__item">Slow networks</li>
				<li class="vf-list__item">Device limitations</li>
				<li class="vf-list__item">Disabled JavaScript</li>
				<li class="vf-list__item">Server outages</li>
			</ul>
			<p>Testing ensures degradation behaviour works as expected.</p>
			</li>
	</ul>
	<h3>Feature Fallback Strategy</h3>
	<p>Overview</p>
	<p>Modern features are used by default, but alternative implementations are provided when those features are unsupported.</p>
	<p>Example</p>
	<p>A website using CSS Grid may fall back to Flexbox or simple float layouts.</p>
	<p>Code example</p>
	<pre class="vf-code-example__pre"><code>
.container {
  display: flex;
}
@supports (display: grid) {
  .container {
	display: grid;
  }
}
	</code></pre>
	<p>
		This allows modern browsers to use advanced layouts while older browsers continue functioning.
	</p>

	<h3>Content Fallback Strategy</h3>
	<p>Overview</p>
	<p>When rich media cannot be rendered, alternative content is provided.</p>
	<p>Example</p>
	<p>If video playback fails, a transcript or image can be displayed instead.</p>
	<p>Code example</p>
	<pre class="vf-code-example__pre"><code>
&lt;video controls&gt;
  &lt;source src="video.mp4" type="video/mp4"&gt;
  &lt;p&gt;Your browser cannot play this video. Read the transcript below.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/video&gt;
	</code></pre>
	<p>
		This ensures the information remains accessible.
	</p>

	<h3>Network Failure Fallback Strategy</h3>
	<p>Systems return cached or placeholder data when external services fail. </p>
	<p>Example: If an API request fails, the application may display previously cached results instead of failing.</p>
	<p>Example pattern</p>
		<ul class="vf-list vf-list--unordered">
			<li class="vf-list__item">API request fails</li>
			<li class="vf-list__item">System loads cached data</li>
			<li class="vf-list__item">User continues interacting with available information</li>
		</ul>
	<p>Example: Handling API failures with fallback data.</p>
	<pre class="vf-code-example__pre"><code>
try {
  const response = await fetch(API_URL);
  const data = await response.json();
  return data;
} catch (error) {
  return cachedData;
}
	</code></pre>
	<p>
		This ensures users still receive information even if the external API fails.
	</p>

	<h3>Component Isolation Strategy</h3>
	<p>Overview</p>
	<p>Independent components are isolated, so failures in one module do not affect the entire system.</p>
	<p>Example</p>
	<p>A failing chart widget should not prevent the rest of a dashboard from loading.
This prevents cascading system failures.
</p>

	<h2 class="vf-u-margin--0 vf-u-padding__top--400 vf-u-padding__bottom--600">Graceful Degradation Vs Progressive Enhancement</h2>
	<p>
		Graceful Degradation and Progressive Enhancement are closely related but follow different design directions.
	</p>
	<p>Graceful Degradation</p>
	<ul class="vf-list vf-list--unordered">
		<li class="vf-list__item">Build full experience first</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Reduce functionality for less capable environments</li>
	</ul>
	<p>Progressive Enhancement</p>
	<ul class="vf-list vf-list--unordered">
		<li class="vf-list__item">Build basic functionality first</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Add advanced features for capable environments</li>
	</ul>
	<p>In practice, both strategies often complement each other. Progressive Enhancement ensures accessibility from the start, while Graceful Degradation helps systems remain resilient after deployment.</p>

	<h2 id="dos-donts" class="vf-u-margin--0 vf-u-padding__top--400 vf-u-padding__bottom--600">Do / Don't</h2>

	<h4>Do</h4>
	<ul class="vf-list vf-list--unordered">
		<li class="vf-list__item">Ensure core features remain accessible</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Provide fallback mechanisms</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Cache important data</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Test under degraded conditions</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Design modular components</li>
	</ul>

	<h4>Don't</h4>
	<ul class="vf-list vf-list--unordered">
		<li class="vf-list__item">Depend entirely on one external service</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Allow one component to block the entire application</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Assume users always have modern browsers</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Hide essential content behind JavaScript</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Ignore failure scenarios during development</li>
	</ul>

	<h2 id="checklist" class="vf-u-margin--0 vf-u-padding__top--400 vf-u-padding__bottom--600">Checklist</h2>
	<ul class="vf-list vf-list--unordered">
		<li class="vf-list__item">Core content remains accessible without advanced features</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Fallback alternatives exist for critical functions</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">External API failures handled safely</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Website usable on older browsers</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Page functional on slow networks</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Redundant infrastructure implemented</li>
	</ul>

